06612nam a22017535i 9780691238272DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20222003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912382727 a10.1515/97806912382722doi  a(DE-B1597)609929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aART0151002bisacsh1 aSandberg, Mark B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving Pictures, Missing Persons :bMannequins, Museums, and Modernity /cMark B. Sandberg. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b77 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late nineteenth century, Scandinavian urban dwellers developed a passion for a new, utterly modern sort of visual spectacle: objects and effigies brought to life in astonishingly detailed, realistic scenes. The period 1880-1910 was the popular high point of mannequin display in Europe. Living Pictures, Missing Persons explores this phenomenon as it unfolded with the rise of wax museums and folk museums in the largest cities of Denmark, Sweden, and Norway. Mark Sandberg asks: Why did modernity generate a cultural fascination with the idea of effigy? He shows that the idea of effigy is also a portal to understanding other aspects of visual entertainment in that period, including the widespread interest in illusionistic scenes and tableaux, in the "portability" of sights, spaces, and entire milieus. Sandberg investigates this transformation of visual culture outside the usual test cases of the largest European metropolises. He argues that Scandinavian spectators desired an unusual degree of authenticity--a cultural preference for naturalism that made its way beyond theater to popular forms of museum display. The Scandinavian wax museums and folk-ethnographic displays of the era helped pre-cinematic spectators work out the social implications of both voyeuristic and immersive display techniques. This careful study thus anticipates some of the central paradoxes of twentieth-century visual culture--but in a time when the mannequin and the physical relic reigned supreme, and in a place where the contrast between tradition and modernity was a high-stakes game.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aA Severed Head.  aAgnosticism.  aAnachronism.  aAnthropomorphism.  aAntique furniture.  aArchive.  aAssassination.  aAutobiography.  aCataclysm (Dragonlance).  aCemetery.  aChamber of Horrors (Madame Tussauds).  aCity Museum.  aComplexity.  aCrone.  aCultural history.  aCurator.  aDeal with the Devil.  aDeath mask.  aDeath.  aDecapitation.  aDecoy effect.  aDegenerative disease.  aDesecration.  aDiorama.  aDismemberment.  aDistrust.  aDocumenta.  aDouble consciousness.  aDreyfus affair.  aEntrapment.  aEphemerality.  aExoticism.  aFalse evidence.  aFirst Sorrow.  aFolk museum.  aFrom Time Immemorial.  aGenre painting.  aGrandparent.  aGrave robbery.  aHis Family.  aHistorical Association.  aHistorical trauma.  aHorror film.  aHyperreality.  aIllustration.  aImpossibility.  aInfidel.  aJonathan Crary.  aKaren Blixen.  aLeprosy.  aLinda Williams (film scholar).  aMail.  aMannequin.  aMemoir.  aMichael Dummett.  aMichael Fried.  aMock execution.  aModernity.  aMorgue.  aMost Secret.  aMuseology.  aMuseum.  aMystery of the Wax Museum.  aNeglect.  aNeoromanticism (music).  aNew Thought.  aNewspaper.  aNight of the Living Dead.  aNightmare in Wax.  aNordic Museum.  aObsolescence.  aOn Cinema.  aOrientalism.  